TI  - Xanthan gum-toughened nanocomposite conductive hydrogel for wearable sensors and smart livestock monitoring.
AU  - Xu, Minglu
AU  - Ge, Rongfeng
AU  - Wang, Wenyu
AU  - Peng, Yunqi
AU  - Li, Zhenchun
AU  - Liu, Wenhua
AU  - Wang, Lei
T2  - International journal of biological macromolecules
AB  - Highly stretchable strain sensors based on conductive polymer hydrogels are rapidly becoming promising candidates for various wearable skin and smart  monitoring devices. However, due to the inherent limitations of low adhesion and  large hysteresis, existing strain sensors are not able to realize their full  potential in applications. In this study, we harnessed the self-polymerization  capability of polydopamine (PDA) to encapsulate silica (SiO(2)) and load Fe(3+)  onto the surface of PDA, resulting in the formation of SiO(2)@PDA-Fe  nanoparticles. We incorporated polyacrylamide (PAM), SiO(2)@PDA-Fe nanoparticles,  MXene, and xanthan gum (XG) into the system, thereby creating a multifunctional  conductive hydrogel (SiO(2)@PDA-Fe/MXene/XG/PAM) characterized by excellent  self-adhesion, impressive mechanical properties (1680 % strain), lack of  cytotoxicity, anti-swelling, photothermal capabilities, and antimicrobial  effects. Furthermore, the hydrogel strain sensor constructed from  SiO(2)@PDA-Fe/MXene/XG/PAM exhibits outstanding sensing properties, including  high sensitivity (GF = 3.14), durability, and stability over 2500 cycles. This  sensor was employed for human motion detection, effectively adapting to the  complex movements of various joints while delivering stable and reliable  physiological signal data. It also serves as a wearable medical patch to monitor  vital signs such as Electrocardiogram (ECG) and Electromyography (EMG).  Additionally, we designed a pressure sensor capable of detecting whether piglets  are pressed by sows, offering a reliable concept to enhance piglet survival  rates, which holds significant potential for practical applications.
