TI  - An open-source lightweight ear-tag mounted sensor for ML-based real-time monitoring of dairy calf activity
AU  - Ouannes, Amenallah Massarra
AU  - Mascret, Quentin
AU  - Petit, Étienne
AU  - Bousselmi, Asma
AU  - Gagnon-Turcotte, Gabriel
AU  - Ahloy-Dallaire, Jamie
AU  - Gosselin, Benoit
AU  - Paquet, Eric R.
T2  - Smart Agricultural Technology
AB  - Monitoring the activities of individual dairy calves is crucial for assessing their welfare and detecting early signs of disease. However, traditional observation methods used by producers are labor-intensive and often fail to capture subtle behavioral changes. Precision livestock farming has introduced various sensor- and video-based monitoring tools, such as commercial activity trackers, RFID systems, and proprietary video platforms. However, many of these solutions are invasive, lack robustness, or are closed-source, which limits adaptability and makes it difficult for researchers to build upon or customize them. In this study, we present a novel, open-source, lightweight ear-tag-mounted sensor designed for real-time monitoring of calf activity. This device integrates seamlessly with machine learning models to offer an automated, non-invasive approach to closely monitor calf activity. The system utilizes the open-source RuuviTag-based sensor housed in a newly designed casing that does not require any additional ear piercing, reducing animal discomfort and pain. The sensor captures triaxial acceleration data at 10Hz, which is transmitted to a Raspberry Pi 4 for preprocessing before being analyzed by machine learning algorithms. These models classify calf activities into three key behavioral states: lying, standing, and drinking. Experiments were conducted on five dairy calves on a commercial farm in Quebec, Canada over one week. While initial simpler models like random forest showed promise with accuracy of 72.5%, a long short-term memory (LSTM) model achieved the highest accuracy of 99% on the test and an average of 93.5% in leave-one-calf-out evaluations, which tests the model's performance on a calf it has never seen before. These promising results highlight the potential of this open-source technology to enhance early disease detection and improve calf welfare through continuous, automated open-source monitoring.
