TI  - Resource-constrained hybrid attention-driven approach for enhanced interpretability and scalability in multi-event livestock condition classification and monitoring
AU  - Shafi, Fariya Bintay
AU  - Ahamed, Md. Faysal
AU  - Khandakar, Amith
AU  - Rohouma, Wesam
AU  - Ayari, Mohamed Arselene
AU  - Reaz, Mamun Bin Ibne
T2  - Results in Engineering
AB  - Precision Livestock Farming (PLF) enhances dairy farming by integrating artificial intelligence (AI) and sensor technologies for health, productivity, and welfare monitoring. However, existing methods remain resource-intensive, difficult to scale, and limited in handling diverse livestock events. To address these challenges, we propose CATT-Net, a lightweight and interpretable hybrid deep learning framework for multi-event livestock condition classification, covering health-related, reproductive, and stress-induced behavioral events. It integrates Principal Component Analysis (PCA) for dimensionality reduction, Squeeze-and-Excitation (SE) blocks for feature recalibration, LSTMs for temporal dynamics, Transformer encoders for global representation, and an Additive Attention mechanism for focused decision-making. Evaluated on four diverse datasets from experimental and commercial farms, CATT-Net achieves high accuracy (99.74 %, 96.10 %, 98.81 %, and 95.85 %) while maintaining efficiency (1.72 MB, 144k parameters, 3.77 MFLOPs), enabling deployment in resource-limited settings. SHAP-based analysis ensures transparency, and ablation studies confirm the contribution of each component. Compared to state-of-the-art transformer models and simpler baselines, CATT-Net achieves higher accuracy while requiring substantially less computational cost. External validation using real-world data from Adorsho PraniSheba, Bangladesh, further demonstrates its practical applicability for livestock monitoring. Code availability: https://github.com/fariya17/CATT-Net
