TI  - Analysis and classification of pig health status using hourly activity data: Combining statistical analysis and machine learning
AU  - Yin, Jianjun
AU  - Chen, Yifei
AU  - Huang, Yigui
AU  - Xiao, Deqin
T2  - Applied Animal Behaviour Science
AB  - Early detection of health issues in pigs is critical for efficient farming and animal welfare. This study employs statistical analysis and machine learning to analyze and classify the health status of pigs using hourly activity data. We collected data from 176 pigs over 145 days using pig ear tags and applied statistical analysis and visualization methods to identify activity patterns associated with normal and abnormal health statuses. Key features, encompassing statistical, peak, and trend features, were extracted to train several machine learning models, including Random Forest, CatBoost, and the CNN_LSTM_Attention (CLA) model, among others. The findings indicated that pigs were most active from 05:00 h to 10:00 h and from 12:00 h to 18:00 h. Compared with normal pigs, abnormal pigs presented markedly reduced activity levels, particularly during peak hours. Pigs with different types of abnormalities demonstrated distinct activity levels compared to normal pigs. Those with cardiopulmonary abnormalities showed declining trends similar to those with spleen and digestive system abnormalities, while pigs with growth and development abnormalities presented the most significant differences compared to normal pigs. The CLA model achieved the highest performance in classifying pig health status, with an accuracy of 89.3 %. This research presents an innovative approach to pig health monitoring and management utilizing activity data, which has significant practical implications.
