AB  - The detection of copper ions (Cu²⁺) is critical in food safety, as excessive intake of Cu²⁺ can lead to serious health complications, including liver damage and neurodegenerative disorders. While accurate, conventional detection methods such as atomic absorption spectroscopy (AAS) and inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry (ICP-MS) are often hampered by high costs and lack of portability for field applications. In this work, glutathione (GSH) functionalized magnetic nanoparticles (Fe₃O₄) were employed for the first time to prepare a magnetic fluid (Fe₃O₄-GSH) exhibiting both high magnetization and superior fluidity. Subsequently, an electrochemical sensor was developed for the sensitive detection of Cu²⁺ in food, leveraging the redox interaction between ferrous iron (Fe²⁺) and Cu²⁺ coordination. The electrochemical sensor demonstrated a linear detection range of 10∼200 nM with a detection limit of 4.83 nM (0.31 µg/mL). Notably, the electrochemical sensor had no obvious cross-reaction with common interfering metal ions while maintaining excellent repeatability and operational stability. These performance characteristics suggest the proposed sensor provides a reliable technical platform for heavy metal ions detection in environmental and food safety applications.
