TI  - Employing a metric to quantify the effectiveness of an agricultural drought early warning system during the fourth industrial revolution
AU  - Masupha, Teboho Elisa
AU  - Moeletsi, Mokhele Edmond
AU  - Tsubo, Mitsuru
T2  - Computers and Electronics in Agriculture
AB  - Evaluating the effectiveness of drought early warning systems is essential for improving their role in informing decision-making during all stages of drought events. This study assessed the Agricultural Drought Early Warning System (ADEWS) in South Africa, with the goal of enhancing its functionality and relevance in the context of the fourth industrial revolution. Data were collected through a content analysis of the ADEWS website, cross-referenced with secondary sources. A ratio-based approach was applied using 27 key performance indicators (KPIs), with calculations performed in R version 4.4.1. Each KPI was assigned a score of one if present and zero if absent, with the total presence expressed as a percentage for each component. The results revealed gaps in the system, particularly in the response capacity for agricultural stakeholders, and a partial presence (38%) of the knowledge of risk component. The monitoring and warning component (71%) and dissemination (67%) were the most prominent, though limitations were identified, such as the absence of field reports, interactive maps, and user-friendly design. The study proposed integrating artificial intelligence algorithms, unmanned aerial vehicles, and extended reality devices into the existing infrastructure to enhance data collection and decision support. Additionally, transitioning to cloud-based hosting and adopting Web 3.0 protocols could improve decision-making capabilities while providing offline functionalities for regions with limited network access. This innovative approach, based on universally accepted components, can be adapted globally to address drought challenges, with broader implications for enhancing agricultural resilience through improved resource allocation, management, productivity, and profitability.
