TI  - Multi-camera multi-cow tracking under non-overhead views
AU  - Xu, Xingshi
AU  - Deng, Hongxing
AU  - Shang, Yuying
AU  - Wang, Yunfei
AU  - Zhang, Shujin
AU  - Chen, Diyi
AU  - Song, Huaibo
T2  - Expert Systems with Applications
AB  - Tracking is a crucial means for effectively monitoring both individual and group health conditions in dairy cows. Existing studies predominantly focus on developing multi-cow tracking algorithms within single-camera system. However, practical applications are hampered by limitations such as blind areas in single-camera’s view field and inconsistent spatial resolution due to non-overhead camera installations. To address these challenges, a Multi-Camera Multi-Cow Tracking (MCMCT) method was proposed, enabling accurate multi-cow tracking over large areas using multiple non-overhead cameras. First, MCMCT achieved geometric mapping between images and the monitoring area by calculating a homography matrix. Second, in the dairy cow detection stage, Quaternion Convolution and Repulsion Loss were integrated into YOLOv8n. The former enhances boundary feature extraction by leveraging color structural information, while the latter reduces bounding box shift by explicitly accounting the spatial relationships between predicted boxes and surrounding bounding boxes, thus improving detection performance under occlusion. Moreover, in single-camera multi-cow tracking stage, Posture-aware Temporal-smooth Embedding (PTE) enables a more stable representation of appearance information, effectively mitigating ID switches caused by substantial appearance variations. Finally, a tracklet association method based on spectral clustering was proposed, which models the tracklet association as a graph minimum-cut problem, enabling cross-camera association of tracking results. Experimental results confirmed the effectiveness of the proposed method. The detector’s AP50-95, the single-camera tracker’s Higher Order Tracking Accuracy (HOTA), and the cross-camera tracklet associator’s ID F1-Score (IDF1) were 84.81 %, 82.68 %, and 82.23 %, respectively, representing improvements of 3.17 %, 2.75 %, and 21.32 % over the Baseline method. These results demonstrated that the proposed method can effectively utilise the multi-camera setup, providing a solid data foundation for dairy cow health monitoring.
