TY  - JOUR
TI  - Advanced graph-theoretical modelling and optimized kinematic path planning for minimizing energy and time in autonomous laser land levelling operation
AU  - Ambuj
AU  - Machavaram, Rajendra
T2  - Next Research
AB  - Uneven terrain has significant adverse effects on agricultural productivity, primarily due to increased weed pressure, non-uniform crop emergence, and variable crop maturity. Precision land levelling has been identified as an effective method to enhance water use efficiency, improve crop establishment uniformity, and ultimately increase yield potential. However, conventional laser levelling systems are often limited by inefficiencies, either due to excessive cut-fill requirements or residual soil displacement, which can lead to non-uniform land surfaces. These limitations are compounded by the manual selection of operator paths, which rely heavily on surface observation and result in suboptimal fuel usage and reduced operational efficiency. To address these limitations, we developed a Genetic Algorithm (GA)-driven navigation system for optimizing land-levelling operations. The GA-based system autonomously generates optimal travel paths by minimizing total travel distance while maximizing the efficiency of soil movement. This approach ensures an ideal cut-fill ratio, achieving balanced soil redistribution across the field. The system was evaluated on three experimental field plots (25 m × 35 m, 20 m × 25 m, and 33.75 m × 20.25 m), achieving a cut-fill ratio close to one, which is crucial for minimizing rework and enhancing uniformity. The maximum observed cuts were 394.85 mm, 55 mm, and 611 mm, with corresponding fills of 345.78 mm, 34 mm, and 618 mm, respectively. The GA-based approach effectively reduced total levelling time by 6.466 %, 9.057 %, and 6.2 %, with completion times of 10.32, 5.91, and 7.44 min, respectively, for each plot. These findings demonstrate the potential of GA-based navigation systems in precision agriculture, suggesting that GA-driven path optimization not only improves resource use efficiency but also enhances the operational precision of land-levelling equipment. This study establishes a foundation for future applications of algorithm-driven field operations aimed at improving agricultural efficiency and sustainability.
