AU  - Sachdeva, Gulshan
T2  - Biomass and Bioenergy
AB  - This study investigates the catalytic performance of Fe and Zn-coated zeolite converters in biodiesel-fueled diesel engines, focusing on emission reduction and performance enhancement. The zeolites were coated with Fe and Zn through a wet impregnation process, followed by calcination at 450 °C. Performance tests conducted on a single-cylinder diesel engine demonstrated significant improvements in engine efficiency and emission characteristics. The Brake Thermal Efficiency (BTE) increased by up to 20 %, from 30 % to 36 %, while Brake Specific Fuel Consumption (BSFC) decreased by 15 %, from 0.38 g/kWh to 0.32 g/kWh. Emission tests revealed a 53 % reduction in carbon monoxide (CO) emissions (3.2 g/kWh to 1.5 g/kWh), a 60 % decrease in unburned hydrocarbons (HC) (0.5 g/kWh to 0.2 g/kWh), and a 45 % reduction in nitrogen oxides (NOx) (5.5 g/kWh to 3.0 g/kWh). Smoke opacity was reduced by 60 % (20 %–8 %), highlighting the synergistic effects of Fe and Zn coatings. These enhancements are attributed to the catalytic activity of Fe in promoting complete combustion and the thermal regulation provided by Zn. This research demonstrates the potential of Fe and Zn-coated catalytic converters to significantly improve biodiesel engine performance while reducing environmental impact. Future work will address the long-term durability of these coatings and explore alternative metal combinations for further performance optimization.
