TY  - JOUR
TI  - Anomaly identification of wind turbine blades based on Mel-Spectrogram Difference feature of aerodynamic noise
AU  - Li, Hao
AU  - Wang, Zhenyu
T2  - Measurement
AB  - Anomaly identification of wind turbine blades is crucial for reducing the maintenance and operational costs of wind turbines. A method based on Mel-Spectrogram Difference feature (Mel-SD) to identify damages in wind turbine blades is proposed. A Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) algorithm is employed to classify wind turbine blade audio datasets. By decomposing the different feature and calculating anomaly evaluation metrics, damaged blade audio signals are discriminated. Subsequently, blade abnormality is identified by comparing the anomaly evaluation metrics with significance-level parameters. To validate the feasibility of the anomaly identification method, experiments were conducted in a quiet wind tunnel with various blade models under different wind speeds, including regular blades, blades with holes, and blades with penetration. 1850 sets of audio data was collected during these experiments. Due to stationary blades being used in the laboratory while actual wind turbine blades rotate, a cycle-fitting algorithm was applied to process the experimental data and establish the experimental dataset. Additionally, the accuracy of discriminating anomaly signals through CNN was validated on the experimental dataset, achieving an accuracy of 98.2%. Based on the analysis of experimental data, the feasibility of identifying blade damages through anomaly evaluation metrics P-value was confirmed. Furthermore, the performance of the algorithm in anomaly identification on measured data was investigated and 3 different types of faults were detected. The results indicated that the algorithm achieved the expected results in identifying damages for measured data.
