AU  - Lemmer, Andreas
AU  - Oechsner, Hans
T2  - Bioresource Technology
AB  - Agricultural residues, especially horse manure, represent an underutilised resource for biogas production. This study investigated mechanical ball mill pretreatment effects on substrate mixtures containing high proportion of horse manure and other agricultural residues in full-scale continuous stirred tank reactors. Experiments compared pretreated and untreated substrate mixtures under continuous and shock feeding scenarios at different organic loading rates. Results showed excellent process stability with consistent pH (7.8–8.0) and ratios of volatile fatty acids to total alkalinity of carbonates below 0.25, indicating robust buffering capacity despite challenging input substrates. Pretreatment significantly improved specific methane yields (from 216 ± 75 LCH4 kgVS−1 to 312 ± 52 LCH4 kgVS−1) and enhanced degradation kinetics. Economic evaluation demonstrated positive energy balances (165.7 to 332.0 kWh tVS−1) across all operating conditions despite energy input for pretreatment. This validates agricultural residues as viable alternatives to conventional energy crops for demand-oriented biogas production, contributing to sustainable renewable energy generation.
