T2  - Biomass and Bioenergy
AB  - The global demand for energy is predominantly met through fossil fuels, which contribute significantly to environmental pollution. Biodiesel produced from sustainable, non-edible feedstocks offers a promising alternative. This study investigates the transesterification of Ceiba pentandra seed oil (CPSO) for biodiesel production. CPSO was extracted with a yield of 18.6 % and initially exhibited a high free fatty acid (FFA) content, which was reduced to below 1 % using an oil-to-methanol ratio of 1:3, 5 vol% H2SO4 catalyst, at 60 °C for 60 min. An L-ascorbic acid impregnated activated carbon (AAIAC) catalyst was prepared and characterised using SEM, BET, TGA and FT-IR techniques. Process optimization was initially performed using Box–Behnken design under response surface methodology (RSM), followed by the development of a more accurate nonlinear model using an artificial neural network (ANN). A genetic algorithm (GA) was employed to identify optimal conditions for microwave-assisted transesterification: an alcohol-to-oil ratio of 30:1, 0.7 wt% AAIAC catalyst, microwave power of 270 W, and a reaction time of 180 s, achieving a maximum biodiesel yield of 95.4 %. The resulting biodiesel was thoroughly characterised using GC-MS, FT-IR, and NMR spectroscopy (1H, 13C, HMBC, and HSQC). Engine performance and emission analyses revealed that a B20 biodiesel blend closely matches conventional diesel, indicating its suitability for use in unmodified internal combustion engines.
